close_reason: Resilient entry/add input hardening delivered end-to-end.
body: "Epic for robust entry ingestion and add command fault tolerance.\n\n## Detailed implementation plan\n\n1. Complete parser and stdin foundation (pm-luay)\n   - Add resilient entry parsing fallback layers in shared parser code: strict csv key=value, markdown-style key:value lines, and forgiving comma continuations.\n   - Add deterministic stdin token support for explicit pipe usage so commands can consume piped payloads safely.\n   - Keep canonical normalization and existing valid inputs fully backward-compatible.\n\n2. Wire command surfaces (pm-0pvk)\n   - Apply stdin token resolution and resilient parser usage to entry/add mutation commands: append body, comments add, files add/remove, docs add/remove, test add/remove, create repeatable entries, and update repeatable entries.\n   - Standardize actionable usage errors with examples for quoted commas, markdown-style pairs, and stdin token usage.\n   - Preserve command output contracts and deterministic mutation behavior.\n\n3. Verification and documentation rollout (pm-s9hl)\n   - Add focused unit tests for parser and command branches plus integration coverage for CLI stdin and markdown-style payload workflows.\n   - Update README, PRD, AGENTS, and CHANGELOG with resilient input guidance and compatibility notes.\n   - Run build plus targeted and broad test suites to verify no regressions for existing users before closure.\n\n4. Closure and evidence\n   - Attach changed files, linked tests, and docs to tasks/features/epic.\n   - Record validation evidence in comments, close tasks/features/epic, and release claims after completion."
